{"/service/ndnp/iune/batch_iune_heron_ver01/data/sn92053739/00542864801/1921010201/0004.xml":{"full_text":"qnrtg{\nI\nip\nR\n\n?i\nNt\n42\nTHIRTY-THIRD YEAR.\nFast Stonis Dail Journal\u2018I\nNO. 2 TWENTY-TWO PAGES SUNDAY MORNING, JANUARY 2, 1921._THREE SECTIONS. Dii PRICE 5 CENTOS\nBUSINESS DEPRESSION VANISHING\nEAST ST. LOUISANS LOOK ON 1921 AS YEAR OF PROMISE\n_\nIMPROVEMENT BOND\nDEFICIT OCCURRED\nBEFORE 1913; SAYS\nFORMER TREASURER\nF. Keating Declares\nLynch Avenue Fund\nWas Only One Intact\nThen.\nWEST SIDE BANK\nTAKES ACTION\nPre sent Treasurer\nWould be Restrained\nin Payment of Bonds\nComing Due.\nThe deficit alleged to exist in the\nspecial improvement fund for the\noutlet sewer, which was disclosed by\na petition of the Mercantile Bank of\nSt Louis, for an order restraining\nCity Treasurer Cholet from retiring\nbonds, dated from a period earlier\nthan May 1, 1913, according to a\nstatement given The Daily Journal\nby Frank Keating, who succeeded\nFred Gerold as city treasurer.\nFred W. Mollman, former mayor,\nin a recent statement, asserted spe\ncial improvement funds during his\nadministration were kept intact, no\npayments being authorized by the\ncity council unless money to meet\nthe vouchers was in the treasury.\nThe Mercantile bank, in the peti\ntion for an injunction, says a $5,000\ndeficit is faced in each of eight in\nstallments remaining unpaid on the'\noutlet sewer assessment, resulting in\nthe improvement bonds being worth\nless than par. The bank also wants\nCholet restrained from retiring the\nbonds on a \u201cfirst come, first served\"\npolicy and to have the money re\nceived paid out on a pro rata basis.\n\u201cThe \u2018jack pot\u2019 system of collect\ning special improvement assess\nments was being followed when I\ntook the office of city treasurer,\u2019\u201d\nBaid Keating. \u201cI refused to accept\nfunds from my predecessor until the\nmoney was distributed over the vari\nous funds as is provided by law.\nBefore this distribution was complet\n<\u25a0<1, however, the bond records were i\nstolen and it was only by checking\nagainst vouchers canceled that we\nwere able to. arrive at a figure each\nfund was entitled to form the \u2018jack j\nI\npot.\u2019\n\"The Lynch avenue improvement\nfund was the only one intact May 1,\n1913. In it was approximately $121,\n000.\n\u201cIt was about this time also that\nthe city council authorized an addi\ntional tax levy of approximately $93,\n000. When the Chamberlin adminis- i\ntration, with which I was connected.\nassumed charge, it was decided not\nemmaad thia law nvar .he -A\nto spread this levy over the books.\nCourt action was taken, however,\nand a mandamus compelling him to\nfollow the order of the prior city\ncouncil was obtained.\n\u201cAfter we succeeded in distribut\ning the money in the treasury at the\ntime I took office, all assessments\npaid during the remainder of my\nterm were preserved in the proper\nfund until used in retiring bonds\ncharged against it.\n\u201cArthur O\u2019Leary, the present com\nmissioner of streets and alleys, was\nthe superintendent of special assess\nments at that time and he was in\ntrumental in having the funds prop\nerly distributed as is provided by\nlaw.\nDuring the remainder of his\nterm he continued the collections as\nthe law provided and there can not\nbe a single Irregularity charged to\nthe Chamberlin administration in the\ncollections and payments of the i\nfunds.'\nThe system O\u2019Leary and Keating,\ninaugurated after it had been dis-'\ncarded by prior administrations is\nstill being followed. The funds re-!\nceived are distributed into the ac-'\ncounts as tne law provides.\nIt is practically impossible now to,\nmake up the deficit said to be faced.!\nThis is accounted for in one way by\nthe fact that some of the property\nowners paid the assessments in full\nand that instead of being spread i\nover 20 installments, as was set\nforth, the payments in full were j\nused in retiring bonds up to the i\ntwelfth installment, along with the i\ninstallments payments as they were\nmade.\nFormer Mayor Mollman\u2019s state-'\nment was printed in Thursday\u2019s is\nsue of The Daily Journal. He con-!\nsidered statements of city officials,\nin which \u201cpoor business methods of\npast administrations\" were blamed,\nas a reflection on his administra\ntion, as did Keating on the Chamber\nlin administration.\n\"Former Mayor Chamberlain is\nnot in East St Louis to make a\nstatement and I believe that in jus\ntice to him and also to myself the\ncondition of the funds when I be\ncame city treasurer should be ex\nplained to the public,\u201d Keating pre\nfaced his statement.\nKeating was asked if under the\nlaw it would be possible to levy an\nother assessment to meet the de\nficit the bond holders say exists. He\nsaid that this was hardly possible as\nthe supreme court has ruled that a\nhouseholder cannot be dispossessed\nof his property to meet a judgment\n(Continued on Page Two.)\nNEW YEAR GOT\nWARM WELCOME\nBY THOUSANDS\nStreet Crowd Greater;\nParties as Numerous\nas Ever.\nEntered into rest at the stroke\nof 12 o\u2019clock. Nineteen Hundred\nTwenty, at the age of one year.\nSuffering during the last moments\nwas partially alleviated by the fre\nquent applications of (say it soft\nly) stimulants slightly stronger\nthan soothing syrup. Please omit\nflowers. Smelling salts appre\nciated.\nThousands of East St. Louisans\nsaw withered and worn Nineteen\nHundred Twenty displaced by the\nyouthful and vigorous Nineteen Hun\ndred Twenty-one; they watched the\nold fellow fight gamely to the last;\nthey saw the new champion finally\nland the kayo and with a \u201ckick\u201d they\nput the finishing touches to the old\nboy.\nOfficially the passing of the old and\nthe birth of the new was dry. But\nthere were many moist spots, and the\nmoisture was not from tears for the\ndeparted. But wet or dry, East St.\nLouis was not to be denied its New\nYear\u2019s eve celebration.\nProbably the best attended party\nwas at the Elks Club, where, under\nthe supervision of the entertainment\ncommittee\u2014Messrs. Cullen, McGlynn,\nMoore, Albrecht and Emmett Griffin,\nexalted ruler\u2014a program pronounced\nthe best in the club's history was pre\nsented.\nThe rathskeller of the club was\njammed. There were miles of multi\ncolored streamers darting comet-like\nthrough the elaborately decorated\nbuilding; cowbells, horns and rattles\nvieing with Crawford's Jaxz band;\ncabaret entertainers without peers in\nthe profession, and, of course,' the\ntissue paper dunce caps for every\none.\nA midnight supper of turkey with\nall the trimmings was served. When\nthe crowd was not dancing, the en\ntertainers kept spirits up. Activities\ncontinued until wee hours of yester\nday.\nAlthough society\u2019s chief gala event\nwas one that will be long remember\ned it did not entirely eclipse the cele\nbrations staged elsewhere.\nThere\nwere dances at most of the halls in\nthe city and there were hundreds of\nparties in the various homes.\nWhile frivolity was at its height\nthroughout the city a more serious\nside of the celebration was n prog\nress at some of the churches. This\ntook the form of watch night serv\nices.\nIntoxication, while not as frequent\nas in former years, was not conspicu-\nous by its absence on the streets of\nthe city. The casual stroller under\nthe white lights and in the outlying\ndistricts glimpsed many of the scenes\nI\nfamiliar on a New Year\u2019s eve of\nI\nformer years.\nThe downtown theaters\u2014Majestic.]\nLiberty and Erber\u2019s aided the\nmerrymakers in welcoming the new\nyear by operating until later hours\nthan usual.\nLarge crowds were in\nattendance at all of them, where New\nYear's programs had been arranged.\nWhile the prohibition agents were\nactive and took every possible step\nto prevent the sale of boose, their\nwork, because of the large number\nof sales in every part cf the city, was\nmost ineffective.\nThe celebrators\nproceeded under the theory that Vol\nstead did not make it an offense\nagainst the government to carry\nliquor internally, and generally when\nthey came from their places of con\ncealment that was the only place\nthey carried any.\nMILITARY HONOR\nWILL BE GIVEN\nCORP. FROELICH,\nEast St. Louisan Who\nDied in France\nBuried Today\nArrangements for a military fun\neral over the body of Harry D.\nFroelich, of 409 North Tenth street,\nhave been arranged for this after\nnoon, at two o\u2019clock, and a large\nnumber of ex-service men are ex\npected to be present.\nFroelich served in France as a\nand\ncorporal in Company \u201cM,\u201d\nInfantry, Thirtieth Division, anu\ndied in France. His body arrived\n119th\nin New York last Tuesday, and in\nEast St. Louis on Saturday after\nnoon.\nMrs. Viola Froelich, his wife, sur\nvives. The services will be held in\nthe Walsh chapel, thence to St Pat\nrick\u2019s church, and Mount Carmel\ncemetery.\nRELEASE SIX FROM\nSMALLPOX QUARANTINE\nSix cases of smallpox were\nre\nleased from quarantine yesterday\nby the Health Department, bringing\nthe number of cases down to twenty\nagain.\nBut one new case was re\nported. The epidemic is becoming\nmilder and since a great number of\npersons have come to the Health\nDepartment for vaccination, it is ex\npected that this will aid materially\nin reducing the number of new de\nvelopments, especially among the\nschool children.\nFIVE INJURED WHEN\nAUTO SKIDS ON FREE\nBRIDGE; CRASHES\nINTO HEAVY GIRDER\nMiss Mildred Harper\nin Hospital With\nBroken Limb\u2014Others\nSlightly Injured.\nMIST CAUSED\nTHE MISHAP\nProgressive Party, in\nThree Autos, Were\nEn Route to West Side\nHome.\nFive East St Louisans were in\njured, one seriously, and two escaped\ninjury early yesterday morning\nwhen an automobile in which they\nwere crossing the free bridge skid\nded in car rails, struck the curb on\nthe north side, spun around and\ncrashed against a suspension girder\non the south. Injured are:\nMildred Harper, daughter of Al\nHarper, 1318 Baugh avenue, the\nmost seriously hurt\u2014broken leg and\nprobable fracture of the left arm.\nKatherine and Rebecca Caughlan,\ndaughters of D. W. Caughlan, 610\nNorth\nbruised.\nEleventh\nstreet slightly\nWalter Griesedieck, son of Frank\nGriesedieck, 443 North Fourteenth\nstreet, and driver of the car\nuts\nand bruises about the head, hands\nand body.\nDavid Caughlan, brother of Kathe\nrine and Rebecca\u2014suffered bruises\nand cuts.\nRussell Orr, son of Mrs. Edna\nOrr, 1741 Cleveland avenue, and\nMiss Louise 'Holly. 428a Columbia\nplace, escaped unhurt.\nPassing motorists took the in\njured to Deaconess hospital, where\nMiss Harper is still a patient.\nGriesedieck left the hospital yester\nday morning, and the others, after\nreceiving emergency treatment, were\nsent home a short time after the\naccident.\nThere were thirteen in a party on\nroute to St Louis. Six were follow\ning in two machines. In one, driven\nby Dan Sprecher, 665 North Thir\nteenth street, were Alice Mace, 600\nNorth Eleventh street; Gladys Fou\nIon, 407 North Eleventh street, and\nErnest McHale, 521 North Twenty\nfourth street. In the second were\nWill Moore, whose address was not\ngiven, and Louise Williamson, 4000\nWaverly place.\nThe girls in the party are mem\nbers of the Shusch club. They en\ntertained New Year\u2019s eve with a\nprogressive dinner party. The last\ncourse was served at the Caughlan\nhome. It was then suggested that\nall drive to St. Louis to witness the\ndeath of the old year in Missouri.\nShortly after midnight they started.\nEarlier in the evening the party\nhad been entertained at the homes\nof Miss Mace, Miss Holly and Miss\nFoulon, in the order named.\nMiss Harper, who is a student at\nWellesley College in Boston, was at\nhome for the holiday season. It will\nprobably be several weeks before\nshe can return to school.\nA heavy mist which settled over\nthis vicinity late Friday evening is\nbelieved to have caused the automo\nbile. which was badly damaged, to\nskid. All in the party say Griese\ndieck, who owns the Griesedieck\nAutomotive Co., was driving slow,\nthe accident occurring at the dan\ngerous curve on the bridge just\nabove the east bank of the river. i\nOne wheel of the machine came\ni\noff when the car crashed against\nthe suspension girder.\nThe wind\nshield was shattered and the cuts\nwere suffered from flying glass.\nFour other automobile accidents\nare said to have occurred at the\nsame point on the bridge early yes\nterday and Friday evening. No oc\ncupants of other cars were injured\nseriously enough to be taken to hos\npitals, however. Some of the ma\nchines were badly damaged in the\n7\nhowever.\ncrashes.\nAMERICAN STEEL\nWILL CUT WAGES\nMany Threaten Resig\nnation Following Re\nduction of 10 Per\nCent.\nA wage cut of 10 per cent, effec\ntive this morning at the American\nSteel plant has been announced, and\napproximately 50 employee of the\nfoundry were said yesterday after\nnoon to have resigned their positions\nrather than to accept the wage cut.\nThere are approximately 1,000 em\nployes at the plant The cut, accord\ning to information received yester\nday, will extend throughout the plant\nAt the plant yesterday it was learned\nthat company officials had not de\ncided whether or not to replace the\nemployes who resigned. Officials of\nthe company declined to discuss the\ncut or resignations, pending the out\ncome of negotiations to be conducted\ntoday.\nw\n20\nCLERKS TO DEMAND\nUNION CARDS FROM\nPLACES REMAINING\nOPEN UNTIL 9 P. M.\nPresident Miss Strautz\nof Local 676 Says Ac\n1 tion Will Be Taken At\nOnce.\ns\nCLERKS MUST\nFOLLOW CARDS\nEmployers Paid for\nExtra Service and\nWill Give a Half Holi\nj day This Week.\nOfficers of Retail Clerks\u2019 Union,\nLocal 676, have listed merchants who\nI failed to close their establishments\ni at 5:30 o'clock Friday evening, as is\nprovided for in the working agree\ni ment between the employes and the\nemployers.\nTomorrow union cards held by the\nmerchants will be demanded and\ni union clerks who fail to follow the\ncard will probably be expelled from\ni the local, according to Miss Jose\nphine Strautz, president of the or\nganization.\ni Hunter Keith, secretary of the\n1 Central Trades and Labor Union,\nwho acted Thursday and Friday as\nmediator between the merchants and\n1 clerks, told The Daily Journal yes*\ni terday he understood K. G. Morton,\nsecretary of the Downtown Business\nMen\u2019s Association, had informed the\nmerchants that he (Keith) on Thurs\nday told Morton that the clerks\ni would arrange to work until 9 p. m.\nI Friday.\n\"I made no such promise to Mr.\ni Morton on Thursday and Friday,\nmeeting Thursday evening\nof the Retail Clerks' Union I visited\nafter a\ni\nOA nit iwuau Vasend viiivu a \u202240998\nI every merchant except Harry Klie,\ni manager of the Schmitz Shro\nI der store, to inform them that the\n1 members of the local had been in\n'trusted to quit at the regular Fri\nday closing hour,\u201d stated Keith.\nThe following letter was read to\nthe merchants by Keith, he said:\n\"A special meeting was called of\n**1, 1. vd Y Daiail flignle?\nthe executive board of Retail Clerks1\nUnion, Local 676, in regard to an\nannouncement in The Daily Journal\nstating that all stores would remain\nopen until 9 p. m. Same was in er\nror, and the merchants are expect\ni ed to abide by their contract, which\n1 means closing at 5:30 p. m., Decem\nber 31. Signed: Josephine Strautz,\npresident; E. J. Allison, secretary.\u201d\nTo clerks in all of the stores Keith\nhad been instructed to communicate\ni an order as follows:\n\u201cUni6n clerks are expected to\nleave their places of employment at\n5:30 p. m., December 31, 1920. as\nper agreement. Signed: Josephine\nStrautz, president; E. J. Allison,\nsecretary.'\nKeith continued: \"When I talked.\nto Mr. Morton I told him I would\nmake an effort to have the elerks\nconcede the later closing hour, but I\ndid nAf nrnmres hrmm that *hav wanld\ndo so.\nnot promise him that they would\nso. It is possible that he misun\nderstood me, but I did not\nmy statement to him. When\nf\narble\nwent\nback to the clerks and reported the\ndesire of some of the merchants to\nremain open they said that the in\nternational board had instructed\nthem to abide by the contract.\u201d\nMr. Morton was out of the city\nand could not be reached far a\nstatement.\nMiss Strautz, when requested for\na statement yesterday, declined at\nfirst to give one, but she added that\nthe executive board would meet to\nmorrow evening to take action in\ncases where the contract had been\nviolated.\n\u201cThe contract has been violated\nand there is only one thing for us\nto do,\u201d she said. \u201cWe will have to\ntake up the cards of the merchants\nwho did not close at 5:30 p. m., as\nhad been agreed. Action against\nthe members of the union who failed\nto follow the contract will also be\nforced and unless they follow the\nunion cards from the stores it will\nbe necessary to place them on the\nunfair list.\u201d\nAmong the stores Miss Strautz\nsaid she learned was open until 9 p.\nm. Friday were Kaminer\u2019s, Schmitz\nShroder, Driedel\u2019s, Zerweck\u2019s\nArcade Furniture stor- Morton\nDriedel\u2019s,\nstore\nBros. Furniture store, Rhodes-Bur\nford furniture store and the Walk\nOver boot shop. Several other small\n(Continued on Page\nCardinal Gibbons\nMach improved\nBaltimore, Md., Jan. L\u2014Cardinal\nGibbons was reported considerably\nimproved today after his relapse of\nThursday.\nMass was said in his\nroom this morning, indicating a great\nchange for the better.\nThe cardinal is at the residence\nof Robert T. Shriver at Union Mills,\nMd. There it was said that there is\nno immediate cause for alarm. His\nIllness is reported due to nervous\nweakness of the heart, brought on by\nover-exertion. His mind is clear and\nvigorous.\nGreat anxiety is felt here today\nand special prayers have been asked\nby Bishop Corrigan.\nINDUSTRIAL LEADERS\nPREDICT GOOD YEAR\nApproach of Stable Basis Seen By Majority\nDiversity of Employment Gives\nCity Big Advantage.\nWith the crisis of the post-war readjustment period believed to be\npractically passed, and a stable basis again almost within reach, East St.\nLouis, because of the widely diversified lines of essential industry, is\nexpected by heads of several of the largest plants to struggle free from\nthe grip of business depression before many weeks.\nAlmost without exception statements obtained by The Daily Journal\nfrom the industrial authorities are optimistic, and resumption of trade is\nlooked for early in the new year.\nIncluded among those from whom\nstatements came are John A. Schaeffer, vice-president of the Eagle-Picher\nWhite Lead Company; F. A. Hunter, general manager of the plant .here\nof Swift Company H. W. Waddell, superintendent of the Armour\nCompany plant; Joseph Nester, president of the Obear-Nester Glass Com\npany; C. B. Fox, president of the Aluminum Ore Company, and James F.\nGalvin, of the McLean Galvin Real Estate Company.\nEast St Louis, during the general\nslump in business of the past six\nmonths, has been affected probably\nless than any other city in the\nUnited States. While it was recently\nestimated by Stewart Campbell,\nsuperintendent of the Illinois Free\nEmployment Bureau, that 5000 per\nsons in the East St Louis industrial\ndistrict are now out of work, this\nnumber as compared with other dis\ntricts of similar population, is far\nbelow the percentage looking for jobs\nelsewhere.\nMr. Schaeffer, whose company is\n1 now erecting in East St Louis the\nlargest and best equipped plant in\nthe United States for the manufac\nture of oxides of lead, and a plant\nsecond in capacity for the manufac\nture of corroded white lead, detailed\nthe negotiations which preceded the\ndecision during the past year to lo\ncate here.\n\"The Eagle-Picher Lead Co. be\nlieves in the City of East St. Louis\nas an industrial center,\" one para\ngraph of his statement reads. He is\nvery optimistic of the future, stat\ning:\n\"The belief which the Eagle-Picher\nLead Company has in the industrial\nfuture of East St. Louis, not only for\nthe year 1921, but also for the com\ning years, is best evidenced by a\nsurvey of this company\u2019s activities\nin this locality during the past year.\nThe greater expansion of this com\npany has centered on East St. Louis\nduring this time.\n\"Prior to the year 1919 the Eagle\nPicher Lead Company had not enter\ned the St. Louie field.\nIn looking\nabout for a proper field for the ex\npansion of their actvities they neces\nsarily sought a place well favored\nby proper transportation facilities, a\ngood labor market, and cheap fuel\nAll these things of such primary im\nportance in manufacturing were be\nlieved and found to exist in East St.\nThis company first entered\nLouis.\nthis field through the purchase of the\nplant of the Hammar Bros. White\nLead Company. immediately after\nobtaining control of this company,\nplans were made for its enlargement\nand betterment, which plans were\ncarried to completion during me past\nyear. The capacity of the plant has\nbeen largely increased. Every im\nprovement for the manufacture of\ncorroded white lead by the old\nDutch process has been installed.\nThe result is that this plant is now\nthe most modern plant for the manu\nfacture of corroded white lead, and\nits capacity is only exceeded by that\nof the Eagle plant of the Eagle\nPicher Lead Company at Cincinnati.\n\"The early part of 1920 plans\nwere made for the erection of a\nplant for the manufacture of oxides\nof lead. Within a few months the\nCity of Bast St Louis can boast of\nnot only the largest, but also the\nbest equipped plant for the manufac\nture of oxides of lead, both red lead\nThese\nand litharge, in the world.\noxides of lead are basic materials,\nwhich so essentially enter into the\nmanufacture of storage batteries,\nglass, enamels, paints, varnishes and\nall allied industries.\n\"Every precantion is being taken\nin this plant for the safety of the\nmen. A welfare house is being pro\nvided for all the workmen. A thor\noughly equipped laboratory is being\nbuilt to take care of the routine work\nand research work attendant to not\nonly the manufacturing processes as\nthey pertain to the manufacture of\noxides, but also a labortory where\nin a study can be made of the in\ndustries in which the use of oxides\nof lead is of primary importance.\n\"All the additions which have been\nmade at the Hammar Bros.\u2019 White\nLead plant and the new plant of the\nEagle-Picher Lead Company are of\nthe most modern construction. These\nplants, when completed, will give\nemployment to approximately five\nhundred men.\n\u201cThe Eagle-Picher Lead Company\nbelieves in the City of East St.\nLouis as an industrial center.\nIt\nalso believes that the coming months\nwill show a pronounced increase in\nindustrial activity in all lines, and\nespecially among those lines which\nare so basically dependent upon the\nproducts which are produced from\nthe plants of this company in the\n(Continued on Page Seven.)\nCITY NEWS IN BRIEF\nit was a quiet New Year's eve In\nEast St. Louis.\nOnly five arrests were made for\ndrunkeness in the last 24 hours and\nthe police hardly knew there was a\nholiday in progress. Up to last eve\nning there was only one arrest for\nviolation of the anti-fire arms order,\nand this was a 13-year-old boy who\nwas enthusiastically firing off a\nsmall pistol when complaints from\nthe neighbors brought the police. Af\ner a lecture the boy was permitted\nto go home.\n\u201cDown with Capitalism.\"t\n\u201cDown with the Capitalilao\nGov\nernment\"\n\u201cHall to the Soviet Government of\nAmerica.\u201d\nThese are the slogans with which\na four-page pamphlet sizzling with\nred-hot attacks on the government,\non the present social order, on cap\nitalism and on about everything else\nas it now stands is brought to a\nclose. These pamphlets which de\nolare revolution in America, and call\nupon the proletariat to rise and take\nover the government, were scattered\nalong St Clair avenue some time\nFriday night\nWhen the St Clair avenue bour\ngeolse got up yesterday it found\nthese startling circulars.\nSeveral\npeople called up the police, and now\na search is on for the person or per\nsons who scattered this inflammatory\nliterature during the dead of night.\nThe pamphlet bears the signature\nof the Central Executive Committee\nCarson Manwarren, of 2715 Sum\nmit avenue, paid two fines of 915 and\ncosts each to Justice Kane Friday\nmorning. At Ohio avenue and Thirty\nfirst street, Manwarren, who was\ndriving a touring car, knocked down\nAudrey De Armond, of 223 North\nThirty-first street, and then tried to\nspeed away, the police say, but his\ncar was stuck in the mud and he\ncould not make his escape. De\nArmond was taken to the Deaconess\nHospital, where it was found that\nhe was only bruised.\nEric Knickmann, 19 years old, of\n484 North Thirtyfourth street, gave\nan imitation of Barnoy Oldfield do\ning his boot Friday evening, and\nwhen Police Sergeant Walker and Of\nScore Scheetz and Heillg finally over\ntook the touring ear he was driving\nwith a police machine, he was doing\n\nI some 40 miles an hour. Knickmann\npaid two fines of $15 each to Justice\nKane for his sport.\nThe negro highwayman who takes\nMs victims to a secluded spot, pre\nferably under the raised sidewalks,\nwhere he can make a through\nsearch, bobbed up again New Year's\neve. A. A. Goodwin, of 3500 Missouri\navenue, was the victim this time.\nAt the point of a revolver the lone\nnegro bandit forced Goodwin off the\nwalk at Missouri avenue and Twelfth\nstreet Friday evening Into a vacant\nlot where he searched him and took\n$10, a gold watch, a pair of diamond\nset cuff buttons and other trinkets\nincluding two gold pencils. Recently\nseveral persons were held up and\nforced to go under raised sidewalks\nby the negro bandit, and the police\nare of the opinion that one man is\nspecializing in this class of stick\nups.\nThere seems to be a serious div\nision in the House of York, 111 North\nB.street, at least the police have been\nsummoned to that number twice\nwithin 12 hours.- The Yorks live on\nthe \"Island,\u201d and their trouble seems\nto be purely a family affair, since\nMrs. Althea York, mother of Floyd\nand George York, Is the complainant\nand the sons are the ones complain\ned about. They were first arrested\nFriday night and went home after\nthey had secured bond, and yester\nday morning the row broke out again,\nand the two sons of York were\nbrought In once more. They again\ngave bond to answer to a series of\nassault and battery, threat to kill and\nassault to kill charges. So far no\nblood seems to have been shed.\nif you drive an automobile and\nfeel you must bump into something,\ndo not pick on a street car because\nthe car company gets peeved if you\nmuM up the nice yellow paint on\ntheir gondolas. At least the car com\npany secured a warrant Friday\nagainst Dr. E. T. Micksick, of 708A\nSt Clair avenue, charging him with\ndoing divers and sundry things to\none of their Eighteenth street cars.\nIt appears that in the fog of New\nYear\u2019s eve Dr. Micksick tried to run\nover the car with his automobile,\nand In the fracas both the auto and\nthe street car were considerably\nmussed up.\nNow the oar company will have\nthe law on the doctor.\n\nU. S. OFFICIALS\nFORECAST LESS\nGLOOM AS NEW\nSEASON COMES\nPrediction of Better 1\nC\nBusiness and Less\nLiving Cost Seen by\nTreasurer.\n.8\nS\nl\nBUYERS\u2019STRIKE Li\nNEARING END i\n_ Q 1\nRegard Reports of Mil-\nlions of Jobless as Ex-\naggerated\u2014No Luxu\nries Being Purchased,\nBy RALPH F. COUCH.\nWashington, Jan. 1\u2014Prosperity,\nlike the flowers of the song, will\nbloom again this spring. The busi\nness depression is already beginning\nto dissolve. 4\nThia, according to government of\nficial* in the treasury, agriculture\nand labor departments, is the fore\ncast for 1921\nIf true, the forecast means an end\nof unemployment now involving\nthousands of workers stabilising\nprices and perhaps lower ones for\nthe consumer. It also will end the\ngreat national buyers\u2019* strike which\nswept the entire country early in the\nsummer.\nEthelbert Stewart, government ex\npert, believes that 1921 prices should\nbe far lower than those obtaining at\npresent\n\u201cBusiness depression would disap\npear within a few weeks if manufac\nturers and retail dealers would give\nup the idea that they can cling to\nwar prices,\" said Stewart. \u201cThe buy\ning public is in need of almost every\nnecessity. If prices were reduced to\na reasonable point there would be a\nnew rush of buyers which would\nturn every factory wheel la\ncountry and blot out unemployn\nalmost immediately.\"\nThe optimistic prediction* of\nernment officials and business\nfor prosperity in the spring mi\nbased on factors now developing.1\nSome of the optimistic faetors ce\nthese: e\nl\u2014Government receipts from n\nury taxes have fallen far below a\nfigures of a year ago, indicating t\npublic has ended extravagant bow\ning for all time. -a\n2\u2014Instead of luxuries the puli\nnow is buying bonds and storks; th\nreport of one big steel conceal shey\nan increase of 5,000 in the numbg\nof owners of common- stock. mS\nerty bond transactions have half\nincreasing for several months, bat\u201d\ners reporting to the government the\nthey cannot get enough of loworw\nnominations to satisfy the demaand,\n3\u2014Food prices will descend to re\nlower prices in next few monthe\nv\nl\ni\ni\nthe result of the bumper cro\nvested in practically all sec\nthe country.\n\n8\n4\u2014Retail prices are undergoing\nsteedy but sure decline, accordas\nto reports from fifty-five cities tsH\nlected monthly by the Labor Deprret\nment The pessimistic factors in they\noutlook are listed by governmente\nficials as follows: SSM\n(a) Nearly 9,000 business fodes\nin 1920 as compared with 6,400 44\nyear. al\n(b) Closing of scores of facten\nin the textile. shoe manufantoi\nand automobile making conleaDi\npart time operation of practicaBjjHH\nthe others. 8.\n(c) Falling prices for raw cottoadd\nnow selling at 13 cents per potide\ninstead of 30 cents, and generi tl\nductions in prices of all fan* siadi\nnets, including wheat, corn and MK\n(d) Unemployment. 7%\n(e) Jobless workers now naaiee\n3,000,000, according to one unotrici\nestimate received here. Most mer\nernment officials, however, rego\nthis as an exaggerated estimale,\nficials at the American Feders\nof Labor estimate that unein,\nment now involves at least 1.004\nworkers. Approximately 100,0004\nroad workers are idle, accordigi\nPresident William H. Johnson of\nInternational Association of 7\nchinists.\n\u20225\nIncome Taxes in\nSpringfield i\n\"e\nSpringfield, HL, Jan. 1 \u2014The. th\nternal revenue collector\u2019s offics-hece\nestimates that more than $a6,00be\n000 will be paid in income tares Bo\nthis district. comprising 72 conntin\nof southern, central and wester Di\nThe taxes for 1920 ate\nnois.\nable any time after Jan. 1-1\nMarch 15.\nApproximately\npersons are expected to pay h\nthis district for 1920.\nIt is believed the present fi\nand economic situation will d\nmany taxpayers to withhold the\nturns until near the time\nMarch 15. 2\n1\nUnmarried men must pay ts\nI all incomes over $1,000. Marri\nare required to pay taxes on t\nditional income over $2,000..\nhundred dollaars additional\nis exempt from taxation for,\n(child under 18 .years of age. $i","height":"29972","width":"20176"}}
